{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_grafton_ver01/data/sn85007266/00415668995/1910122201/1352.xml":{"full_text":"The Wallace Miner\n\n\n_ _ __i-\nD\u00abv\u00abu 4 to tfe Wmi intorMi* Mthv *aImm SUtrkt,givias\nmm\\f ulkgntic mfon\u2014titn iimI aiming to accomplish tbU without foot or foror.\nPubUfkMl E.\u00abry T lwn ii y\nGEO. F. STONEY. KuMitos Editor\n1\nWilhrti IJ U\nConor Stk oad Book Slrooto.\nMarch 14. 1\u00ab07. at tha portoOc. at Wallace, Idaho, undar th.\nAct of Congroo of March S. 117V.\nXiiU'rat at second claw matter\nsuMOsimoN Mies\n$2 00\nOita Mar. in adranoa.\nVia month*, in advant\nFOKJEtON\u2014Canada atul aii countrte* in thaunion.\n1\n06\niii'adritiica.\n2 SO\nonaraar.\nIt is not the intention to send\nTHE MINER to any person whose t\nsubscription has expired. If you\nare receiving the paper and are\nplease remit promptly\nto avoid missing any issue. The\nsubscription price is $2 per annum\nPUBLICITY IS PROFITABLE.\nThe Miner has been a consistent adherent of regular re\nports to stockholders. Our position In this matter was hap\npily endorsed a few days ago when a heavy investor from an\neastern state in discussing various Coeur d'Alene properties\nin which he is Interested made this remark about one particular\ncompany: \"I have a lot of money in that company and a nu\nher of my friends are also heavily Interested, but I would never\ncomplain, nor would any of nly friends, if we loet every dollar\nof our investment, because we have been treated so well. We\nhave been kept fully informed about the progress of the work\nand everything pertaining to the property. We have con\nfidence in the management on this account and are thoroughly\nsatisfied.\"\n\nThis is only one Instance of the correctness of our position.\nMany of our subscribers have commended us for the stand\ntaken and not a few operators are with us. In this one di\nrection we feel that we have accomplished something for\ninvestors and incidentally, through publishing these reports,\nhave made The Miner far more valuable to those interested\nin the district. In fact we know of scores of places where\nthis paper is kept regularly on file and we are frequently called\nupon to supply missing copies for these files.\n\nIn this connection we desire to say again to all mine man\nagers that we will be happy to publish their official reports\nin full, when not excessively long, and in cases where they are\nof great length to publish a digest of any report officially issued.\n\\\\e wish it distinctly understood by both mine operator and\ninvestor that we are working for the benefit of the district,\nendeavoring to give and get a square deal for both the man!\nwho puts up the money for development and the man whot\nhi.s the responsibility of getting the best results from its ex\npenditure, and we think our three years' conduct of The Miner\nwill bear out this assertion.\nLOW PRICED STOCK IS NOT ALWAYS CHEAP.\nA dividend-paying security may be selling at a lower price\nper share than a security representing an undeveloped mine;i\nbut if such salient features as capitalization, etc., are inves\ntigated, it may be found that the dividend payer does not re\npresent the same proportionate interest for its one share,that\nthe other proposition does.\n\nIn like manner two development companies may be put\nout with the same capitalizations, and the same apportionment\nof stock to the treasuries; and while the one may offer its stock\nr t a much less price than the other, the higher priced one may\nin the end prove the cheaper.\n\nStock is dear at the loweet nominal figure when it proves\nloss to the purchaser and Is cheap at 25 cents a share for a\nprospect when the money raised actually goes into the ground\nand develops a dividend-paying mine.\n\nLet us better illustrate this point in finance by the over\ndrawn incident of the two men who sought a seller of mining\nstocks, by reason of the big profits which one of their neighbors\nhad made in mining,\nstocks were the same, and when the broker opened up his drawer\nand displayed the certificates he had on hand, the prospective\n\"investors\" got busy sorting out the pretty one*, and loaded\nUp to the limit of their means because they were both pretty\nand cheap. Could you imagine these same men putting up\ntheir good money for a cow, barren of milk, just because she\nlooked pretty and was sold at a low price\u2014for a milker? j\nA HOUSE CLEANING WHICH HAS PURIFIED.\nThe orgte of, promotion, which was brought about by the j\ncombined Influences of the prosperous business conditions;\nand the wild excitement attending sensational mining devel- j\nopments, is a thing of the past, with a resulting increased min-:\noral output, as well as some sincere regrets for souvenirs of\nthe experience.\nT|&\na\nIhese men thought that all mining\nL&V\nThe development attained such proportions that it fell\nof its own weight, even though the business depression helped\npuncture the inAation. There has been a repentance on the\npart of those who blindly took any offered bait which appeared\ninviting; and there is repentance on the part of those who\nhave been made to suffer for the unscrupulous work which\nthey did, in consequence of the opportunity presented to\nunload cats and dogs, or any other kind of thing that the law\npermitted them to incorporate. Publicity laws and federal\nindictments have been direct results of the boom, and it is'\ni to be expected that at least there will be more care exercised,\ni and lese daring sailing close to the rocks attempted, than was\nthe case before.\nTHE HEYBURN BILL.\nThe bill introduced by Senator Heybum to remit assess\nment work on mining claims which were in the Are-swept area,\ndoes not, we believe, meet with the approval of the general\npublic here. There are always a number of people who at\ntempt by one means or another to avoid doing the requisite\nassessment work, and it Is argued that this is the particular\nclass which will reap the full beneAt from the bill. In other\nwords people feel that it will simply mean an added incentive\nto idleness and permit the tying up of valuable mineral land\nin violation of the law, but legalized by special act of congress.\n\nThe great majority of those who are honest In the devel\nopment of their property have already done their work and\nconsequently will not receive any beneAt from this special le\ngislation, while the laggard can continue to idle and laugh at\nhis more ambitious neighbor's unnecessary outlay and effort.\nView of Tamarack Sc Ches\napeak mine which is expected\nto begin production when the\nnew Hercules mill is com\npleted.\n\n'J?\n1C\ntS)\nTHE WHITE CANYON\nCOPPER COMPANY\nOffers for sale 100,000 Shares of Treasury Stock at\n15 cents. Proceeds will be used to install a leaching\nplant. The property is well equipped with machinery\nwhich is all paid for. The ore produced here sells for\n2 cents above the current market price. It is hoped\nto pay monthly dividends upon installation of\nmachinery. 500,000 shares retained in the treasury.\n13 MINING CLAIMS OWNED\nIN SAN JUAN COUNTY, UTAH.\nFor further particulars address the officers\n\nCapt. H. M. McKerr-Kastan, Pres.\nA. E. Wayland, Secy.\n624 Peyton Block,\nSpokane, Wash.\n(Si\n.r\n1\nR. B. BOHANNON,\nBROKER.\nPhoM Mta 5551.\nSIS Mohawk Bid*, Spokono, Wad\u00bb.\nCoeur d'Alene Stocks a Specialty\nTwelve years practical experience in mining in\nthis district puts me in a position to give reli\nable information on all Coeur d'Alene stocks.\nAny order given me will receive prompt and\nconscientious attention.\nHcfcrcnc.i Any bank or Buoinaao houao In W.ltoM.\nATTENTION\nA chance to get in on the ground flpor. Company re\nports monthly. Over two-thirds of the capita} stock in\ntreasury. Nine claims, crossed twice by Railroad. 7,500\nfget on the ledge. Splendid showing. Need money for\nmachinery. Write for Engineer's report. Don't miss this\nopportunity. It costs nothing to find out.\nAddress Box 14, Mullan, Idaho, Dept A.","height":"21264","width":"13704"}}
